A hermetic horror with a claim to psychologism and a political context. In 2002, Jonathan Liebesman's debut horror was panned by critics, but it was liked by the public and earned well at the box office, and most importantly, it caught the eye of producer Michael Bay.
That's how the young director ended up at the factory, churning out new horrors according to old patterns: Bay set himself the goal of re-shooting the entire horror classics in the form of remakes, and commissioned Liebesman to make the prequel to "The Texas Chainsaw Massacre" (2006).
Critics grimaced again, but the public liked it again - Leibesman worked in the spirit of the "new scary ones", emphasizing the excessive physiology of violence.
In general, his example can be used to observe how an entire genre writhes in convulsions, trying to invent new ways of influencing an overstimulated audience: the naturalistic gore of splatter films merges with the chase scenes of slasher films.
The plot is reminiscent of the "Saw" franchise, but without liters of blood.
Among the prototypes is the debut film by Vincenzo Natali, Cube. The film is no longer made by Michael Bay.
So in "Death Room" Libesman was forced to take a different path: instead of a mindless slaughter or a monotonous chase from a maniac, he preferred a smarter option - almost without the notorious bloodshed, but with psychological games and riddles.
