The history of the creation of the Facebook network
David Fincher's new film is, first and foremost, a story about a paradox.
The film tells about the invention of Facebook, one of the pioneering tools in the field of the Internet, which united the whole world, estranged five friends and made its creator, 26-year-old former Harvard student Mark Zuckerberg, the youngest billionaire of the last decades.
Jesse Eisenberg in the lead role is as great as our conflicted genius, emotionally isolated social outcast with an unpredictable set of motivations and attachments.
Zuckerberg is launching the site for a variety of reasons: partly out of frustration with the world, partly out of a sports interest, and partly just because it's "cool."
The very idea and its implementation may seem spontaneous and spontaneous, but the actual course of events suggests a clear calculation and a well-thought-out business plan.
The strengths of "The Social Network" become apparent from the first frames, especially in the scene before the opening credits, where Zuckerberg talks in a bar with his ex-girlfriend Erica (Mara): the ringing, tough dialogues of the screenwriter Aaron Sorkin gain strength here and do not soften until the very end.
The same goes for Fincher's directing: relatively restrained (with the exception of the Winklevoss twins, who were played by actors who didn't look alike.
The face of one of them, with the help of computer graphics, was superimposed on another.
Natalie Portman studied at Harvard at the same time as Zuckerberg.
Runee Mara got the lead role in Fincher's next film, "The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo."
Director David Fincher
STARRING: Jesse Eisenberg, Andrew Garfield, Ruffalo, Justin Timberlake, Armie Hammer, Josh Pence
SYNOPSIS: The gloomy and introverted Harvard student, Mark Zuckerberg, having turned a corner in his personal life, takes on the ambitious task of creating a fundamentally new social network.
As Facebook's popularity grows, relationships with a few close friends begin to fray and eventually lead to lawsuits.
The color palette plays its role: warm, sometimes sunny, even in the dark it remains cozy, it maneuvers between two tangled chains of events and two separate lawsuits.
Outside the stream of endless discussions in the film, not much happens: not a single death, not a single murder, and all of Zuckerberg's legal troubles hardly warrant even an additional paragraph for his meager Wikipedia page.
What attracted 49-year-old Sorokin and 48-year-old Fincher to this story, which is not very rich in details?
After watching, there is a persistent feeling that "The Social Network" is a portrait of our time, and the incompleteness in this case is an important artistic device.
Just about twenty years ago, Wall Street was doing roughly the same thing, only on a larger scale, with space egos and big deals.
Now, when the daily purchasing power has become even higher, the policy is no longer carried out at board meetings or in sandboxes.
Zuckerberg wants to be special, he dreams of becoming the center of attention.
Severin (Garfield) is hurt that his best friend has a new best friend (Timberlake) and now he has no one to play with.
The Winklevosses (Hammer and Pence), meanwhile, are tapping their feet: who said that rich, beautiful, and athletic people can't also be smart?
(This line particularly amuses Fincher.)
If desired, a black comedy could well come out of The Social Network.
Zuckerberg is obsessed with the idea of popularity and leadership, but what is more in his case - positive or negative?
And what social consequences will his invention entail?
Is he a crook?
Or a cunning manipulator?
Fincher and Sorkin will never close the book if there is the slightest hint of something like that.
But here it is not even necessary: in their version of history it is not important at all.
"What's it like to feel beautiful?" asks the song by Tre VerdeNez, "Vabu Wotse A Vspm Map," that precedes the credits.
The hero does not know.
The film suggests the answer.
Zuckerberg is a representative of the lost online generation, which has a weak idea of beauty and even less of feelings.
