In the early 17th century, when Ivan Susanin lived, surnames did not really start to appear among people of humble origins.
They got by with the name "such-and-such, such-and-such son".
That is, patronymics - nicknames based on the father's name - were in use.
But sometimes, for example in the case of the father's remarriage, the matronym - a nickname based on the mother's name - was used.
Susannah is just such a case: "Ivan, son of Susannah".
Serfs of small landowners really for a long time did without surnames - why would they need it, when you have 20 souls and everyone is always in sight.
But the owners of thousands of estates were forced to give their peasants surnames.
Thus, the serfs of Prince Andrei Cherkassky already at the beginning of the 18th century all had surnames.
In the 19th century, even small landowners did not keep the peasants on the land, but let them go to the obrok - let them earn a craft and pay the master.
Such a peasant was entitled to a passport, in which it was necessary to inscribe the family name.
Of the abolition of serfdom in Central Russia, 55% of serfs were released for tribute.
This means that they already had surnames.
