The head of the regulator, in particular, noted that important changes have occurred recently.
On the one hand, the terms of foreign trade have noticeably deteriorated - the price of Russian oil has fallen.
On the other hand, the situation in the economy is developing better than the October forecast.
The shift in the structure of demand continues: consumption remains restrained, private investment is slowing down, but budget expenditures are growing.
At the same time, overall inflation risks increased.
"Therefore, this year the likelihood of raising the rate exceeds the likelihood of lowering it.
The appropriateness of changing the rate will be determined by the development of the situation," said E. Nabiullina.
In addition to the more pronounced impact of fiscal policy, she noted three risks.
First, the rapid acceleration of consumption in the context of increased inflationary expectations, if the factors that restrain consumer activity weaken.
Second, a growing shortage of labor and a lag in productivity growth relative to wage growth.
And there are still risks of additional tightening of sanctions restrictions.
Speaking about the future decisions of the regulator, the Chairman of the Bank of Russia noted that, despite the previously noted strengthening of pro-inflationary factors, the forecast for inflation for the current year remains at 5 - 7%.
According to her, this may require a higher trajectory of the key rate than was assumed in October.
