The crossing on the Armenian-Turkish border was opened for the first time in decades to deliver humanitarian aid
The Margara-Aldzhan border crossing on the Turkey-Armenia border was opened for the first time in three decades to deliver humanitarian aid to earthquake victims.
This is reported by Turkish and Armenian media.
The same crossing was used to deliver humanitarian aid from Turkey to Armenia after the devastating earthquake of 1988, notes the Turkish agency Anadolu.
On Saturday, Armenia sent five trucks with 100 tons of food, medicine, water and other emergency aid packages to the city of Adiyaman in southern Turkey, said Serdar Kilic, Ankara's special representative for Armenian-Turkish negotiations.
He expressed gratitude to the Vice Speaker of the Parliament of Armenia Ruben Rubinyan and the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs of Armenia Vahan Kostanyan.
"I will always remember the assistance provided by the people of Armenia to alleviate the suffering of our people in the earthquake-stricken region," Kılıç wrote on his Twitter account.
The press secretary of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Armenia, Vahan Unanyan, in turn, reported that trucks with humanitarian aid crossed the border through the Margara bridge and are heading to the earthquake-stricken region.
As Public Radio of Armenia reports, the last time the car crossed the Margahar bridge was 30 years ago, in 1993.
Since then, the Armenian-Turkish land border has been closed.
The Turkish agency "Anadolu" cites other data and writes that the border point of Margara-Aldzhan was last used for the delivery of humanitarian aid to Armenia to eliminate the consequences of the devastating earthquake of 1988.
At that time, aid collected through the Turkish Red Crescent was sent to the disaster zone in Armenia.
Earlier, Armenia sent 27 rescuers to Turkey and another 29 rescuers to the earthquake-stricken areas of Syria.
According to the latest data, more than 25 thousand people died in Turkey and Syria from the devastating earthquake that occurred on Monday.
On February 11, Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan reported that 21,848 deaths were already known in Turkey.
The Syrian side reported 3,553 deaths.
Relations between Turkey and Armenia are overshadowed mainly by the fact that Ankara refuses to recognize the Armenian genocide in the Ottoman Empire, and also supported Baku during the First and Second Karabakh wars.
Recently, Yerevan and Ankara have made a number of attempts to normalize relations.
In 2021, Armenia and Turkey appointed special representatives who met several times in Vienna to discuss issues of normalization.
In February 2022, commercial air traffic between Yerevan and Istanbul resumed after a two-year break.
In July 2022, Ankara and Yerevan agreed on the possibility of opening the land border for citizens of third countries as soon as possible.
